pan style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Leeds, Liverpool, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nottingham and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ities are a unique and united local authority voice to promote the role of our ci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ties in driving economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We represent the councils of the 8 largest city economies outside of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These cities drive local and underpin national economies. Working in partnership, we aim to enable each city to enhance their economic performance and make them better places to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">live, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> visit and do business.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ities group has a track record of 15 years as a cross party group, led by the city leaders. It is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">self-selected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and funded group.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> urban areas deliver 27% of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s wealth and are home to one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">third of the country’s population.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Cities are though punching below their weight – our second tier cities should be more economically successful compared with cities of similar scale and r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le in other European and OECD Co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">untries.  For example just for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Core C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ities to punch their weight at the national average would provide the country with an additional £1.3 billion per annum.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Transport infrastructures require radical improvement to maximise economic growth and support improving quality of life an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d the local environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur governan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce and services are fragmented. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Capital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enjoys the benefits of a strategic transport body, Transport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with an integrated single set of policy and investment powers to plan for transport in the cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ital. Across our core cities there is no equivalence which can ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transport maximises economic, socia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l and environmental benefits – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are operating under a structure that is heavily centralised to central government. Excluding recent cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nges to business rate local retention, which makes little difference in this respect, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 95% of all tax raised in English Cities goes to national government.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ranks only 34th in the world for its infrastructure, 6th in the G8 countries, and only spen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds 1.5% of GDP on infrastructure compared to 6% in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Japan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and 3% in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">France</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Public transport investment in the capital now stands at £644 per head compared with £243 per head for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the North of England combined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s performance is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">critical to the nation, but Core Cities are important too and in fact deliver more economically.  The capital has enjoyed very significant transport investment over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the last two decades. Over the last 20 years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has benefited from the implementation o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f significant new transport infrastructure, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thames</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> link</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Jubilee Line extension, upgrades for the Olympics, and HS1 we estimate this to be around £40bn. The rest of the country has on the other hand benefited from the West Coast Main Line upgrade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, New Street Gateway, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and under construction the Northern Hub, around £12bn. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With HS2 most of our great cities will be connected, so they can become a single and powerful engine for economic growth. However to maximise this it is imperative to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maximise connectivity within and between Core Cities. The Transport network has a crucial role in supporting growth and rebalancing the  economy. Independent forecasts demonstrate that our Core Cities have the potential to deliver an additional 1.16 milli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on jobs and £222 billion into the national economy by 2030. Supported by Core Cities research Oxford Economics, Arup and Volterra have estimated that there is a potential for HS2 to deliver a further 400,000 additional jobs in the Core Cities and support t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he delivery of 1 million jobs in total across the wider urban area.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Chair of the Committee, Louise Ellman MP, has said: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“There have been a number of changes in the arrangements for funding and delivering transport projects locally. We want to investigate the complex network of bodie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s involved in local transport decisions and find out how they work together both within and across local authority boundaries. We are also interested in hearing about the different funding schemes that are available and the extent to which these meet local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> needs.”</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:430.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The key messages from the Core Cities in relation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to this line of inquiry are the need for:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Greater certainty of funding for local transport</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A move to the approach of funding of TfL with a stable, single pot</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Longer periods for funding streams </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for local transport in alignment with national transport bodies e.g. 10 years</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A simplification of the system of funding without the many, short – notice, competitive bids to fund a variety of local transport provision</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A simplified delivery model based on T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">fL</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genuine localism with less central government “strings attached”, based on earned trust and track record of delivery locally</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘Duty to Co-Operate’ in respect of the Highways Agency and Network Rail</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Involvement in Policy development for Rail Franchising, Aviation and Seaports </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Enhanced flexibility, to the level enjoyed by TfL, in maximising public transport benefits, including reviewing Transport Levy Referendum arrangements and simplify public transp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ort contracting processes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto;"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Core Cities response to the inquiry questions are outlined below.</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:506.9pt"><p style="margin:0pt"></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q1. What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Governments proposals were welcome, based as they were on the rationale that they can be focused on providing local areas with flexibility to ensure priorities meet local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needs and be proactive to lever in economic development. Whilst it did not reduce the number of funding pots, Major Scheme, Integrated Transport ITB and Capitalised Maintenance blocks, local control over all 3 meant less silo based approach to transport fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nding and a more integrated approach to solutions.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The positive experience of devolution in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is also reflected in Europe where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">European</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Regions have far more influence over their local transport networks in terms of planning, managing and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developing and running these networks than is the case in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outside of London TfL. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">France</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for example a transport tax on salary is provided directly to the local authorities for transport and allows their Mayor to for example stand on a mandate to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deliver a tram in their first 5 year term. A key reason why so many more cities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">France</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are benefiting from modern urban transport systems.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty of funding is also key, the initial allocation of 4 years is welcome however as part of their City Deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> some Core Cities negotiated a 10 year deal (6 years fixed, 4 years indicative). This should be extended to all Core Cities. Such certainty of funding is a key requirement for the current ongoing review of future operating models for the Highways Agency.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Assurance requirements required by the DfT have however effectively required the same assessment requirements and techniques, such as WEBtag, which has resulted in little or no saving in respect of scheme appraisals. It is not uncommon for the cost of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ppraisal to be upwards of 10% of the scheme construction cost.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the period beyond 2015, Major Scheme funding and prioritisation was devolved to Local Transport Bodies constituted of LEPs, ITAs and other key stakeholders. However in 2013, the requirement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Strategic Economic Plans by LEPs, which includes Major Scheme and ITB funding within the associated Single Local Growth Fund, now leaves the role and function of ITAs and LTBs in this regard under question. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A single allocated pot comprising all capita</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l funding streams should be made available to all Core Cities, based on the TfL model, as a 10 year allocation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Advantages</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A single pot of funding as outlined for a 10 year period will provide certainty over funding and appropriate planning, development an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d prioritisation. We believe this should become a permanent on-going arrangement, bring local transport for Core Cities into alignment with the national transport bodies and Transport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Big improvement on previous process of annual Funding Settle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment approach which left little time to plan accordingly</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allows for programme flexibility especially to react to external influences or opportunities e.g. ability to capture and support new development opportunity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disadvantages</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2010, the reduction in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e number of funding pots available from the DfT was combined with major reduction in capital allocations. In 2009/10 for example the total West Midlands Metropolitan Area capital allocations via all funding streams was £77.062M. For 2011/12 the same capita</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l allowances was £41.071M, a 47% cut. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Major Scheme funding devolution to LEP areas means the ability to fund larger strategic schemes is not seen to be feasible. A scheme of £20M </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approx.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is now effectively the largest scheme which could be practically fun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ded through the Major Scheme allocations for 2015-19</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Devolution of Major Scheme funding to local areas could have been an opportunity for Local Areas to reduce development costs and speed up approval timeframes, however imposition of WEBtag based appraisal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requirements by Government is likely to see such benefits minimised.</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:436.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q2. Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Governments original rationale of devolution was to empower local areas and allow flexible, dynamic transport government and delivery structures reflective of local economic geographies. However, Government does appear to have contradicted this approach by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> imposing new structures and bodies, Local Transport Body’s LTB’s, rather than allowing local determination towards transport through the exiting local authority processes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most of the Core Cities effectively have 8 different organisations undertaking sim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ilar transport functions: Core City, Integrated Transport Authority ITA, Passenger Transport Executive PTE as promoter and deliver of Passenger Transport schemes, LTBs prioritising Major Schemes, Local Enterprise Partnerships developing SEPs and promoting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic development which includes access to transport funding with the Single Growth Fund, Highways Agency, Network Rail and DfT for rail franchises. In practice, the differing remits, funding and covering geographies is likely to lead to inefficiencies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between strategic planning, development and delivery of schemes and initiatives.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A model similar to London TfL for Core Cities would greatly simplify and streamline the system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the significant cuts in Local Authorities is obviously having an impact,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the ability for local authorities to determine their appropriate processes and structures together with certainty of funding, would greatly reduce the resource requirement. This together with a reduction in the overdependence of national government of com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">petitive bids, 3 major bidding rounds in 2013 alone, would greatly assist with capacity.</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:436.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q3. What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the Core Cities, strategic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cross boundary transport planning across the travel to work areas is vital and reflects the realities of transport patterns and requirements of an urban area both for internal cross boundary movements and wider within the economic catchment of the metropo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">litan area.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Again, the differing bodies, organisation an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d authorities covering varying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> geographical areas with different responsibilities towards funding allocation, strategic planning and delivery is likely to lead to inefficiencies between strategic plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ning, development and delivery.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the West Midlands for example, whilst the ITA is presently tasked by the Local Transport Act (2008) to undertake strategic cross boundary transport planning, decision making on Major Schemes is now undertaken by 3 separat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e LEP/ LTBs who have a specific focus on promoting economic development, covering different geographical areas to existing structures such as ITAs/ Shire Counties and their Metropolitan District Authorities. There is a danger such a focus misses other tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sport needs and priorities such as connecting people to jobs, addressing severe road congestion, reducing environmental impacts.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a number of other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> moving toward a model similar to that of a Combined Authority which will see the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Leaders directing Transport Strategy and Policy within the wider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">area.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To enable this model to work effectively however the Core City’s and their regions need a mechanism akin to ‘duty to cooperate’ not only with adjacent authorities but also with the High</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ways Agency and Network Rail and be involved in Policy development in respect of Rail Franchising, Aviation and Seaports.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:437.75pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q4. How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core Ci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ties believe that local bodies largely do work well together, a number have or are implementing Combined Authority models. This reflects historical working processes and relationships. However, there does need to a stronger responsibility for national tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sport agencies, such as the Highways Agency and Network Rail, to work closely with local bodies such as ITAs and LEPs to ensure alignment between local needs and their investment programmes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core Cities itself has a Cabinet arrangement, led by Sir Richard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Lease, Leader of Manchester with each of the Core Cities Leader’s having a portfolio. Sir Albert Bore having the Transport Portfolio. Supporting this are a number of working groups that share good practice and help make a collective case for better transp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ort in their areas.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:437.75pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q5. Do the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As previously stated there has been a significant cut in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport capital spend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> although the significant proposed increase in the last spending review is acknowledged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> notwithstanding that a significant proportion of this is not within the li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of this parliament. For example the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has seen a signi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ficant reduction in capital funding blocks. In 2009/10 total West Midlands Metropolitan Area capital allocations via all funding streams was £77.062M. For 2011/12 the same capital allowances was £41.071M, a 47% cut. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition there is as previously sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted a significant funding gap with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public transport investment in the capital now stands at £644 per head compared with £243 per head for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the North of England combined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s performance is critical to the nation, but Core</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Cities are important too and in fact deliver more economically.  The capital has enjoyed very significant transport investment over the last two decades. Over the last 20 years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has benefited from the implementation of significant new transport infr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">astructure, including Thameslink, Jubilee Line extension, upgrades for the Olympics, and HS1 we estimate this to be around £40bn. The rest of the country has on the other hand benefited from the West Coast Main Line upgrade, New Street Gateway, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and under construction the Northern Hub, around £12bn. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment in any transport scheme is a highly efficient approach to supporting the economy as materials are purchased, jobs are created in building the scheme and it improves productivity of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wider economy. It is estimated that for every £1 invested in construction generates £1.86</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Whilst the Government has recognised this and has increased funding for national agencies to historical high levels for the period 2015-19, local tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sport funding (covering Major Schemes, Integrated Transport and Maintenance Blocks) for 2015-19 is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£2.244bn per annum compared to £1.968Bn in 2009/10 an increase of 14% or the equivalent of 1.9% per annum.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ring fencing of conc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">essionary fares budget i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s also helping to distort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local transport support spending and can now account for around 50% of most authorities public transport spending.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q6. What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt; text-indent:-7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Single Local Growth Fund (SLGF) is an opportunity for the underinvestment in local transport to be addressed as discussed in previous answers. But it must be recognised that the majority of the funding is disproportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ately from local transport pots, Major Schemes, ITB and Local Sustainable Transport Funding LSTF </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and as such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adds another element in the local transport framework in an area and could possible lead to a democratic deficit.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite this the £2bn per annum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pot is a welcomed start, however given the competitive nature of the fund, the government still retains control over funding allocations – against the premise of devolution. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The original Major Scheme and ITB Funding was formulaic, a significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proportion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of this, over 50%, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is now competitive.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a question re the future role of the LTB’s beyond 2019 that has yet to be addressed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A more equitable solution would be for the complete devolution of this fund, and other transport sources, to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and their regions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so that they can focus the resource on urban areas which are often the focal point of journeys, hubs of economic activity, population growth and therefore the location where investment in transport issues will generate the largest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefits. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:437.75pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q7. How can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Government’s approach will allow for investment in smaller scale schemes l (&lt;£20M </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approx.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) and larger schemes (&gt;£500M </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approx.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) by the national agencies/ companies, the ability to fund ‘mid-range’ schemes i.e. £20M - £500M locally, vital for transforma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tional changes to local area economies, is considerably more challenging. Mid-range schemes across conurbations largely cover rapid transit (light rail and bus), rail schemes or stations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This means funding opportunities for these types of schemes will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focus on sovereign/ private investment funds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, EIB and general borrowing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with repayment through a mix of fare box, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">council tax levy increases (noting the Governments statutory requirements for a local referendum to facilitate such increases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Such a mechani</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sm was agreed with Leeds City Deal only for it to be subsequently legislated against!), Workplace and Congestion Charging, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Tax Incremental Financing or private sector contributions through mechanisms such as the Community Infrastructure Levy. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To maximise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Transport requirement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enable Core Cities to operate at their full potential in terms of Growth and GVA requires significantly enhanced flexibility, to the level enjoyed by TfL, in maximising public transport benefits, including reviewing Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Levy Referendum arrangements and simplifying public transport contracting processes.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These funding approaches all require the promoting area/ authority to take on financial risks/ guaranteed investment returns not otherwise required by the public funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the smaller scheme or national schemes identified above. Equally, such investment funds expose themselves to risk that result in projected patronage and revenues being optimistic. Such risk is therefore priced into schemes, inflating costs or returns.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With small schemes and nationally significant schemes not exposed to such risks, Government could expedite delivery through underwriting risk to provide a proportionate balance of risk between the public and private sector. For example, the DfT presently u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nderwrites new rail services for a period of time until patronage, revenues and operating costs become established to inform further decision making. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If a similar approach was applied to mid-range schemes, the public sector funding could pump-prime a sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eme with a long term concession then let after a pre-determined number of years. Once the public sector underwriting period was complete and revenues known, growth and operating costs could be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">modelled and valued with certainty. The capital raised from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concession could then be recycled to fund other mid-range transport schemes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With such measures in place, the lower cost of risk built into financial models and decision making by local areas and the private sector would be reduced by creating an enviro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nment of greater funding certainty to unlock investment to create jobs and growth.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:437.75pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q8. How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Core Cities already consider there to be strong lines of local democratic accountability, however </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is concern re the potential accountability in respect of LEP’s and SEP’s. For the Local Growth Fund it needs to be the case that democratic accounta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bility is a key requirement. However </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the spirit of devolution, local areas should be allowed to develop appropriate structures to undertaken government requirements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rather than imposing structures. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It could be argued that at present the national gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nments organisational and technocratic hold over local transport decision – making in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outside of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is overriding the local decision making particularly in areas such as bus deregulation and train franchising to the local electorate to too grea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ter degree.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after all is recognised as having one of the most centrally controlled governance structures in Europe (Second Tier Cities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – Professor Michael Parkinson)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Page </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>